articles.headline: China Ties Aiding Europe to Its Own Trade Goals
articles.snippet: Premier Wen Jiabao offered to help Europe but demanded that it renounce a main legal defense against cheap Chinese exports.
articles.abstract: Premier Wen Jiabao offered to help Europe but demanded that it renounce a main legal defense against cheap Chinese exports.
articles.lead_paragraph: BEIJING — If China is going to help ease Europe’s financial crisis, silken strings could be attached.

articles.headline: House Is Expected to Pass Bill Aiding New Boeing Plant
articles.snippet: The House is expected to pass a bill Thursday that will nullify an antiunion complaint by the National Labor Relations Board, which wants the work moved to Washington State.
articles.abstract: The House is expected to pass a bill Thursday that will nullify an antiunion complaint by the National Labor Relations Board, which wants the work moved to Washington State.
articles.lead_paragraph: Leading House Republicans on Thursday will take up the contentious debate over the National Labor Relations Board’s efforts to block Boeing from operating a $750 million aircraft assembly line in South Carolina instead of Washington State.

articles.headline: Islamists’ Growing Sway Raises Questions for Libya
articles.snippet: Long repressed by Col. Muammar el-Qaddafi, Islamists are now emerging as the best-organized political faction in the country, with influence beyond their numbers.
articles.abstract: Long repressed by Col. Muammar el-Qaddafi, Islamists are now emerging as the best-organized political faction in the country, with influence beyond their numbers.
articles.lead_paragraph: TRIPOLI, Libya — In the emerging post-Qaddafi Libya, the most influential politician may well be Ali Sallabi, who has no formal title but commands broad respect as an Islamic scholar and populist orator who was instrumental in leading the mass uprising.
articles.byline: By Rod Nordland and David D. Kirkpatrick

articles.headline: Seeing Ripple in Jewish Vote
articles.snippet: Republicans are hoping to seize on unhappiness among some Jewish voters over the president’s treatment of Israel.
articles.abstract: Republicans are hoping to seize on unhappiness among some Jewish voters over the president’s treatment of Israel.
articles.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Not since Jimmy Carter in 1980 has a Democrat running for president failed to win a lopsided majority of the Jewish vote. This has been true during times of peace or war, and even when there has been deep acrimony between the White House and the Israeli government.

articles.headline: Automakers and U.A.W. Still Talking
articles.snippet: The United Automobile Workers agreed early on Thursday to extend contracts with General Motors and Chrysler after new deals were not reached by a midnight deadline.
articles.abstract: The United Automobile Workers agreed early on Thursday to extend contracts with General Motors and Chrysler after new deals were not reached by a midnight deadline.
articles.lead_paragraph: DETROIT — The United Automobile Workers agreed early on Thursday to extend contracts with General Motors and Chrysler after the parties were unable to reach new deals by the time the old pacts expired at midnight.

articles.headline: In India, Online Retailers Take a New Tack
articles.snippet: Online retailers in India are going to great lengths to gain customers by allowing them to pay in cash on delivery and by fielding couriers to help ensure quick shipments.
articles.abstract: Online retailers in India are going to great lengths to gain customers by allowing them to pay in cash on delivery and by fielding couriers to help ensure quick shipments.
articles.lead_paragraph: BANGALORE, India — Several months ago, when Prabhu Kumar could not find a book he wanted in bookstores here, he found it online at Amazon.com for $10. But he had to pay more than $9 in fees to have Amazon ship it to him.

articles.headline: 5 Central Banks Move to Supply Cash to Europe
articles.snippet: A coordinated effort to provide an infusion of United States dollars to European banks — the first such show of force in a year — lifted global markets.
articles.abstract: A coordinated effort to provide an infusion of United States dollars to European banks — the first such show of force in a year — lifted global markets.
articles.lead_paragraph: FRANKFURT — Worried that Europe’s debt impasse posed a growing threat to the global financial system, the world’s major central banks moved Thursday to assure that European banks would not run short of cash as troubled nations like Greece and Italy sought to stabilize their economies.
articles.byline: By Jack Ewing and Stephen Castle
